The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Tapan Biswas, 38, was found unconscious near a country liquor shop off Sahitya Parishat Street, in north Calcutta, on Tuesday night. Local residents took him to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital, where he was pronounced dead. Acting on a complaint filed by Tapan?s uncle Kalipada Dey, police arrested the manager of the liquor shop, Sital Saha, and another employee, Achintya Saha. The owner, Sushanta Saha, is absconding. Tapan was a resident of Munshipara Lane. 

 The charred body of 27-year-old Mallika Basu was recovered from the bathroom of her father Ganesh Chandra Biswas?s residence at 25, Kalidas Singh Lane, in the Ahmerst Street police station area, on Wednesday evening. Police said the body had over 80 per cent burns. Mallika was rushed to the NRS Medical College and Hospital, where doctors pronounced her dead. 

 Governor Gopalkrishna Gandhi on Tuesday said the new generation is aware of what it means to be globally connected. Speaking at an interactive session organised by Bengal Initiative on Looking into the Future, the governor said he was looking forward to a harmonious future for the country. 

 A fire broke out at a plywood shop at 40B, Chittaranjan Avenue at 4.45 am on Wednesday. Four fire engines rushed to the spot and doused the blaze by 6.10 am. The cause of the fire was not known.

 A fire broke out at the hawkers? market near Icchapore Rifle Factory, on the northern fringes of the city, on Wednesday afternoon. Twenty-four shops were damaged. 

